'''Gray L. Dorsey''' (died July 20, 1997) was an [[United States|American]] law professor. He was professor emeritus of international law at [[ Washington University in St. Louis]], and had been the Charles Nagel Professor of Jurisprudence in International Law. He had also been president of the [[International Association for Philosophy of Law and Social Philosophy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F4825580AD34869&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Gray L. Dorsey |date=July 22, 1997 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |page =5B |accessdate=24 January 2010}}</ref>
He was the subject of a [[festschrift]], ''Law, culture, and values: essays in honor of Gray L. Dorsey''.<ref>{{cite book|title= Law, culture, and values : essays in honor of Gray L. Dorsey |editor=Sava Alexander Vojcanin|publisher=Transaction Publishers|location=New Brunswick, N.J., U.S.A.|year= 1990|pages=300 |isbn=0-88738-305-X }}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last=Golash |first=Deirdre |year=1993 |journal=International Criminal Justice Review|volume=3|pages=114–116 |issue=1 |doi=10.1177/105756779300300115 |title=Book Review: Law, Culture, and Values: Essays in Honor of Gray L. Dorsey}}</ref>
Dorsey was born in [[Hamilton, Missouri]].
