{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}
[[File:Samue-worn-2006.jpg|thumb|A samue being worn.]]
{{Nihongo|'''''Samue'''''|作務衣|}} is the work clothing of [[Japan]]ese [[Zen]] Buddhist monks, worn when engaged in [[samu (Zen)|samu]].

Made from [[cotton]] or [[linen]] and traditionally dyed brown or [[indigo dye|indigo]] to distinguish them from formal vestments, samue are worn by monks of most Japanese Buddhist traditions performing labour duty such as temple maintenance and field work.  

In modern times they have become popular as general casual or work wear. [[Shakuhachi]] players today, because of the instrument's historical association with Zen Buddhism, sometimes wear samue.

